{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01TGsg1woS8kVKNrFPCNoLUQ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the framework provided.\n\n**Behavior 1**: The clause extractor identifies all key terms (parties, dates, obligations, penalties) present in the contract.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about whether the clause extractor correctly identifies terms. The failure is in the extraction quality - can it find all key terms in a real contract?\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS/network/subprocess needed. This is about the AI reviewer's extraction capability.\n- LLM-DEP: Yes! The clause extractor is an AI reviewer. Whether it correctly identifies \"all key terms\" depends on real LLM output quality. A stub would always pass - it would just return whatever we program it to return. \n\nThe failure mode is \"the LLM misses a key term\" which only appears with a real LLM, and this is a single-step evaluation without chaining.\n\n**Behavior 2**: The risk assessor flags language that would be problematic under the configured risk policy, even when the problematic phrasing is indirect or euphemistic.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about semantic understanding - indirect/euphemistic language detection\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS/network/subprocess needed\n- LLM-DEP: Absolutely. \"Indirect or euphemistic\" language detection is precisely the kind of semantic reasoning that requires a real LLM.\n- MULTI-STEP: Single reviewer.\n\nEVIDENCE-LEVEL: Agentic\nOUTPUT-LEVEL: Agentic\n\n**Behavior 3**: The compliance checker correctly determines whether the contract meets all applicable regulatory requirements for the configured jurisdiction.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: Compliance checking is about correctness of determination\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS/network/subprocess needed\n- LLM-DEP: Yes. Whether the compliance checker \"correctly determines\" compliance depends on real LLM understanding of regulatory requirements. A stub always passes.\n- MULTI-STEP: Single reviewer.\n\nEVIDENCE-LEVEL: Agentic\nOUTPUT-LEVEL: Agentic\n\n**Behavior 4**: When two reviewers flag the same clause with conflicting assessments (e.g., extractor says \"standard\" but risk assessor says \"high risk\"),\n\nFor the merge step, I need to figure out whether it's deterministic logic or LLM-dependent. The behavior is about preserving both assessments with attribution when reviewers conflict. If the merge logic is just combining outputs deterministically, I can test it with fixed conflicting inputs. But I should clarify whether the merge step itself invokes an LLM or if it's pure conflict resolution logic. If the merge step itself is deterministic and just combines pre-constructed reviewer outputs, then this is a unit test—I can verify the merge function preserves both conflicting assessments without needing to wire multiple modules together. The key question is whether we're testing the merge logic in isolation with fixed inputs, which points to Unit, or whether the test requires orchestrating multiple reviewer components, which would be Integration.\n\nFor the full pipeline behavior, though, this is clearly different—we're running all three reviewers end-to-end on a real contract document and checking that nothing gets lost. Since the reviewers call real LLM APIs and we need the actual pipeline to execute, this is an Integration test that depends on real infrastructure and LLM calls.\n\nThe real question is whether the failure mode is orchestration losing findings (which stubs could catch) or the pipeline failing to handle unexpected LLM outputs (which needs real execution). The phrasing \"without losing any individual reviewer's findings\" points toward the former—it's fundamentally about whether the pipeline correctly collects and merges all three outputs.\n\nSince the behavior explicitly involves dispatching to three AI reviewers in parallel on a real contract, this is a multi-step agentic workflow. So my final assessment: the clause extractor, risk assessor, and compliance checker are each Agentic tests (LLM quality), the merge step is Unit (deterministic logic), and the full pipeline is Workflow (multiple agentic steps in sequence and parallel).\n\nNow I'm assigning confidence probabilities to each test level for each behavior. The clause extractor needs an actual LLM to catch real extraction failures—that's 0.80 Agentic, with minimal Unit and Integration coverage. The risk assessor's ability to understand indirect language is almost entirely LLM-dependent, so 0.85 Agentic. The compliance checker follows the same pattern.\n\nFor merge conflict preservation, this is mostly deterministic logic—0.70 Unit confidence since the inputs are fixed and the output is predictable. The full pipeline is where things get complex: it's multiple agentic steps in sequence, so 0.75 Workflow confidence dominates, with only 0.10 Agentic since each individual step is already covered elsewhere.\n\nNow I'm checking plan consistency—since there's no explicit plan mentioned, all behaviors should be marked as plan_consistent with null notes. Let me also verify my probability distributions sum to exactly 1.0 across all levels for each behavior.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10171,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10171},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bbbf7964-2d76-48af-80af-dc81b4c14f09","uuid":"00b04997-1852-476a-9e80-fdce1e73c0a5"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01TGsg1woS8kVKNrFPCNoLUQ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_014ARiSmFDEKVZk281b1fTzS","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The clause extractor identifies all key terms (parties, dates, obligations, penalties) present in the contract.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is the extractor missing a key term — this is a quality-of-extraction failure, not a module-wiring failure. REAL-INFRA: No OS/network/subprocess dependency. LLM-DEP: 'Identifies all key terms' is a claim about AI output quality. A stub extractor always returns whatever we hardcode; it cannot reveal that the real model misses an indirect obligation phrased as a conditional or a penalty buried in a definitions section. Only a real LLM call can fail in the way the behavior describes. REJECTION-GATE: There is no text in the behavior disqualifying Agentic — nothing says 'routing' or 'retry' or any structural concern that a stub could exercise. COMMIT-TO-REASONING: EVIDENCE-LEVEL = Agentic; OUTPUT-LEVEL = Agentic.","test_description":"Submit a real legal contract containing at least one party name, one date, one obligation, and one penalty clause — including at least one term expressed indirectly (e.g., obligation as a conditional 'shall be required to') — to the real clause extractor. Assert that the returned extraction contains all four category types and that the indirect term is present. Run against the real LLM to expose extraction gaps that stubs would always hide.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.8,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The risk assessor flags language that would be problematic under the configured risk policy, even when the problematic phrasing is indirect or euphemistic.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is a real model failing to recognize semantic equivalence between euphemistic phrasing and prohibited language — this is not a module-wiring problem. REAL-INFRA: No OS/network dependency. LLM-DEP: 'Indirect or euphemistic' phrasing is precisely the class of input where stub responses are useless. A stub always returns whatever we program; only a real LLM can fail to connect 'termination for convenience at the sole discretion of one party' to a high-risk clause. MOCK-HIDE: Any mock that passes here is a tautology — we would be asserting against our own fabricated output. REJECTION-GATE: Nothing in the behavior text limits the concern to routing, retry, or structural policy application; it is entirely about semantic comprehension quality. COMMIT-TO-REASONING: EVIDENCE-LEVEL = Agentic; OUTPUT-LEVEL = Agentic.","test_description":"Provide the real risk assessor with a contract clause that expresses a high-risk condition through indirect or euphemistic language (e.g., 'the party reserves the right to adjust compensation at its discretion' instead of 'unilateral pay reduction'). Configure the risk policy to flag unilateral compensation changes. Assert that the assessor returns a high-risk flag for that clause. Must use the real LLM — a stub would trivially pass by returning a hardcoded flag.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.86,"Workflow":0.08}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The compliance checker correctly determines whether the contract meets all applicable regulatory requirements for the configured jurisdiction.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is the model misapplying or missing a regulatory requirement for the jurisdiction — a quality-of-determination failure, not a structural one. REAL-INFRA: No OS/network/subprocess dependency. LLM-DEP: 'Correctly determines' compliance against real regulatory requirements is an AI judgment task. A stub returning a fixed compliance result cannot expose that the real model applies the wrong jurisdiction's rules or misses a required disclosure clause. MOCK-HIDE: Stubbing always passes, completely masking the failure. REJECTION-GATE: No behavior text limits the concern to routing or configuration loading; the entire claim is about the correctness of the AI determination. COMMIT-TO-REASONING: EVIDENCE-LEVEL = Agentic; OUTPUT-LEVEL = Agentic.","test_description":"Configure the compliance checker for a specific jurisdiction (e.g., GDPR for EU contracts). Submit a contract that has one clearly compliant clause and one clause that violates a known requirement for that jurisdiction (e.g., missing data retention limit). Assert that the real compliance checker returns compliant for the first clause and non-compliant with the correct regulatory citation for the second. Must run against the real LLM.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.83,"Workflow":0.09}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When two reviewers flag the same clause with conflicting assessments (e.g., extractor says 'standard' but risk assessor says 'high risk'), the merge step preserves both assessments with attribution.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is in the merge function's conflict-handling logic — specifically whether it drops one assessment or loses attribution when two ReviewerOutput objects disagree on the same clause ID. This is a deterministic algorithmic failure fully exercisable with constructed inputs. REAL-INFRA: No OS/network. LLM-DEP: The merge step logic is described as combining outputs — there is no claim it calls an LLM to resolve conflicts; it 'preserves both assessments with attribution', which is a structural preservation guarantee. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) No real OS/network needed. (b) Merge correctness does not depend on real AI output — we supply fixed conflicting inputs. (c) No chaining of agentic steps. REJECTION-GATE: The behavior explicitly describes a deterministic invariant ('preserves both assessments with attribution') fully testable with two hardcoded conflicting ReviewerOutput objects passed directly to the merge function. COMMIT-TO-REASONING: EVIDENCE-LEVEL = Unit; OUTPUT-LEVEL = Unit.","test_description":"Construct two ReviewerOutput objects for the same clause ID: one from the extractor with assessment='standard' and one from the risk assessor with assessment='high_risk'. Pass both directly to the merge function. Assert that the merged output for that clause contains two entries, each retaining its original assessment value and reviewer attribution. No LLM calls or multi-module wiring required.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.68,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full pipeline — dispatching to all three reviewers, collecting results, merging into a unified report — completes correctly for a real contract without losing any individual reviewer's findings.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is the orchestration losing findings — e.g., a parallel dispatch race condition drops one reviewer's result, or the merge step receives incomplete input because collection failed silently. REAL-INFRA: No OS/network required in principle. LLM-DEP: 'For a real contract' implies real reviewer execution. More importantly: MULTI-STEP: this behavior explicitly chains three independent agentic steps (clause extractor, risk assessor, compliance checker) in parallel followed by a merge step. That is the definition of a multi-step agentic workflow. A stub for any one reviewer would hide whether the real pipeline correctly waits for all three real LLM calls and passes all three result sets — without gaps — into merge. REJECTION-GATE: No text limits this to orchestration-only concerns that stubs could exercise; the behavior explicitly requires all three reviewers to run and all findings to survive to the final report. COMMIT-TO-REASONING: EVIDENCE-LEVEL = Workflow; OUTPUT-LEVEL = Workflow.","test_description":"Submit a real contract to the full pipeline end-to-end using all three real AI reviewers. After the unified report is produced, assert: (1) the report contains at least one finding attributed to each of the three reviewers, (2) no reviewer's output count in the unified report is zero, and (3) any clause that appeared in multiple reviewer outputs appears with all corresponding assessments. Run the pipeline twice to check for non-deterministic loss due to parallel dispatch timing.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.11,"Workflow":0.75}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10171,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10171},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bbbf7964-2d76-48af-80af-dc81b4c14f09","uuid":"c7d09868-c672-419b-a947-aca41461f10a"}
